    "summary": "The Siege of Tyre (332 BC) was one of the most remarkable engineering achievements of [[event:75|Alexander the Great's Empire]]'s campaign, requiring seven months to capture the ancient Phoenician city that sat on an island roughly a kilometer off the coast of what is now Lebanon. Alexander needed to capture Tyre to neutralize the Phoenician fleet that was the core of Persian naval power and prevent his flank being threatened while he advanced into Egypt.\n\nTyre's island location made it seemingly impregnable — previous besiegers including the Babylonian Nebuchadnezzar had failed after multi-year sieges. Alexander's solution was to construct a massive causeway (mole) from the mainland to the island, using rubble from the abandoned mainland city. The Tyrians fought fiercely, using war galleys, fire ships, and catapults to attack the mole and its workers. It was only after Alexander assembled a substantial fleet from Greek allies that he was able to complete the assault by sea. When the city fell, Alexander massacred some 8,000 defenders and sold perhaps 30,000 more into slavery — a brutal punitive act designed to discourage future resistance. The causeway he built remains today as the neck of the peninsula connecting what was once the island to the mainland.",
